[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:litestar-python/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In computer science, a **type signature** or **type annotation** defines the inputs and outputs of a function, subroutine or method.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] A type signature includes the number, types, and order of the function's arguments.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] One important use of a type signature is for function overload resolution, where one particular definition of a function to be called is selected among many overloaded forms.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In C and C++, the type signature is declared by what is commonly known as a function prototype.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Notice that the type of the result can be regarded as everything past the first supplied argument.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] This is a consequence of currying, which is made possible by Haskell's support for first-class functions; this function requires two inputs where one argument is supplied and the function is "curried" to produce a function for the argument not supplied.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Thus, calling `f x`, where `f :: a -> b -> c`, yields a new function `f2 :: b -> c` that can be called `f2 b` to produce `c`.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] The actual type specifications can consist of an actual type, such as `Integer`, or a general type variable that is used in parametric polymorphic functions, such as `a`, or `b`, or `anyType`.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Since Haskell supports higher-order functions, functions can be passed as arguments.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] This function takes in a function with type signature `a -> a` and returns data of type `a` out.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In the Java virtual machine, *internal type signatures* are used to identify methods and classes at the level of the virtual machine code.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Example: The method `String String.substring(int, int)` is represented in bytecode as `Ljava/lang/String.substring(II)Ljava/lang/String;` .
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] A function signature consists of the function prototype.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] It specifies the general information about a function like the name, scope and parameters.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Many programming languages use name mangling in order to pass along more semantic information from the compilers to the linkers.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In addition to mangling, there is an excess of information in a function signature (stored internally to most compilers) which is not readily available, but may be accessed.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Understanding the notion of a function signature is an important concept for all computer science studies.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] The practice of multiple inheritance requires consideration of the function signatures to avoid unpredictable results.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Computer science theory, and the concept of polymorphism in particular, make much use of the concept of function signature.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In the C programming language, a signature is roughly equivalent to its prototype definition.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In the ML family of programming languages, "signature" is used as a keyword referring to a construct of the module system that plays the role of an interface.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In computer programming, especially object-oriented programming, a method is commonly identified by its unique **method signature**, which usually includes the method name and the number, types, and order of its parameters.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] A method signature is the smallest type of a method.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In C, the method signature is the method name and the number and type of its parameters, but it is possible to have variadic parameters, but these are not type-safe.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Manipulation of these parameters can be done by using the routines in the standard library header `<stdarg.h>`.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In C++, in addition to the C-style function return type appearing before, the return type may also follow the parameter list, which is referred to as a trailing return type.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] The difference is only syntactic; in either case, the resulting signature is identical.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Note `void doSomething(auto... args);` is equivalent to `template <typename...
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In Java, a method signature is composed of a name and the number, type, and order of its parameters.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Return types and thrown exceptions are not considered to be a part of the method signature, nor are the names of parameters; they are ignored by the compiler for checking method uniqueness.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] The method signatures help distinguish overloaded methods (methods with the same name) in a class.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Return types are not included in overloading.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Only method signatures should be used to distinguish overloaded methods.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Variadic parameters in Java are represented with ellipses on the final parameter.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] These behave identically to an array, but in the JVM bytecode the method is marked variadic.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] The types in the arguments are used for the multiple dispatch.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] The return type is validated when the function returns a value, and a runtime exception is raised if the type of the value does not agree with the specified type.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Abstract types are allowed and are encouraged for implementing general behavior that is common to all subtypes.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] The above function can therefore be rewritten as follows.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In this case, the function can accept any Integer and Real subtypes accordingly.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] Types are completely optional in function arguments.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] When unspecified, it is equivalent to using the type Any, which is the super-type of all types.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] It is idiomatic to specify argument types but not return type.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] In the Objective-C programming language, method signatures for an object are declared in the interface header file.
[src:litestar-python/type-signature] defines a method `initWithInt` that returns a general object (an `id`) and takes one integer argument.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:litestar-python/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
